fr:mainmatter.fr:p:
We first dicussed an example that indicates the different situations in which we might want to perfom a substitution:


    \usepackage {bussproofs, amsopn, amssymb, mathrsfs, amsmath}
    \newenvironment {bprooftree}
      {\leavevmode \hbox \bgroup }
      {\DisplayProof \egroup }

    \begin {bprooftree}
      \AxiomC {$\vdots $}
      \UnaryInfC {$E^\alpha (x) , O^\alpha (s\, x) \vdash  \exists  \beta . N^\beta (s\,x)$}
      \AxiomC {$\vdots $}
      \UnaryInfC {$E^\alpha (x) \vdash  O^\alpha (s\, x)$}
      \LeftLabel {\small  (cut)}
      \BinaryInfC {$E^\alpha (x) \vdash  \exists  \beta . N^\beta (s\,x)$}
    \end {bprooftree}


  We could imagine the cut (implemented with implication elimination) being reduced and inducing a substitution of the right-hand proof tree for O^\alpha (s\, x). There are four different possibilities that we identified for the structure of the left-hand proof tree, each of which require different handling before and during substitution.


    \usepackage {bussproofs, amsopn, amssymb, mathrsfs, amsmath}
    \newenvironment {bprooftree}
      {\leavevmode \hbox \bgroup }
      {\DisplayProof \egroup }

        \begin {bprooftree}
          \AxiomC {$\vdots ^*$}
          \UnaryInfC {$*\ \ E^\alpha (x) \vdash  \exists  \beta . N^\beta (s\,x)$}
          \LeftLabel {\small  (wk)}
          \UnaryInfC {$E^\alpha (x) , O^\alpha (s\, x) \vdash  \exists  \beta . N^\beta (s\,x)$}
        \end {bprooftree}



    \usepackage {bussproofs, amsopn, amssymb, mathrsfs, amsmath}
    \newenvironment {bprooftree}
      {\leavevmode \hbox \bgroup }
      {\DisplayProof \egroup }

        \begin {bprooftree}
          \AxiomC {$\vdots ^*$}
          \UnaryInfC {$E^\alpha (x) \vdash  \exists  \beta . N^\beta (s\,x)$}
          \LeftLabel {\small  (wk)}
          \UnaryInfC {$*\ \ E^\alpha (x) , O^\alpha (s\, x) \vdash  \exists  \beta . N^\beta (s\,x)$}
        \end {bprooftree}



    \usepackage {bussproofs, amsopn, amssymb, mathrsfs, amsmath}
    \newenvironment {bprooftree}
      {\leavevmode \hbox \bgroup }
      {\DisplayProof \egroup }

        \begin {bprooftree}
          \AxiomC {$\vdots ^*$}
          \UnaryInfC {$*\ \ O^\alpha (s\, x) \vdash  \exists  \beta . N^\beta (s\,x)$}
          \LeftLabel {\small  (wk)}
          \UnaryInfC {$E^\alpha (x) , O^\alpha (s\, x) \vdash  \exists  \beta . N^\beta (s\,x)$}
        \end {bprooftree}



    \usepackage {bussproofs, amsopn, amssymb, mathrsfs, amsmath}
    \newenvironment {bprooftree}
      {\leavevmode \hbox \bgroup }
      {\DisplayProof \egroup }

        \begin {bprooftree}
          \AxiomC {$\vdots ^*$}
          \UnaryInfC {$O^\alpha (s\, x) \vdash  \exists  \beta . N^\beta (s\,x)$}
          \LeftLabel {\small  (wk)}
          \UnaryInfC {$*\ \ E^\alpha (x) , O^\alpha (s\, x) \vdash  \exists  \beta . N^\beta (s\,x)$}
        \end {bprooftree}

  In cases 2 and 4 we imagine that the weakening rule instance can occur anywhere along the cycle (i.e. not necessarily directly above the companion).

  The idea is that in the left-hand cyclic subproof, either the "even" or "odd" assumption can be weakened away, either before or after forming a cycle. We are considering what would happen if we tried to substitute O^\alpha (s\, x) with something. Our intution for how to handle each case is as follows:

The weaking instance is just removed, since the "odd" assumption doesn't interact with the cycle at all.

We need to unfold the cycle once, then the substitution can be performed, removing the weakening step wherever it occurs. We may need to appeal to bud freshness. Side note: does this still work if O^\alpha (s\, x) is used in an axiom, but anything implied from it is weakened away?

We should unfold once, then propagate the weakening to the axioms for O^\alpha (s\, x), then we can substitute.

    Alternate approach: we weaken along the cycle first, but this requires the cycle term variable substitution to be identity for x (\theta  is "good" for E^\alpha (x))

We should unfold once, then propagate the weakening to the axioms for O^\alpha (s\, x), then we can substitute.

    Alternate approach: push weakening along the cycle first, then unfold and we can perform the substitution. This seems to just be the same as the other approach though.

Given a weakening instance:


    \usepackage {bussproofs, amsopn, amssymb, mathrsfs, amsmath}
    \newenvironment {bprooftree}
      {\leavevmode \hbox \bgroup }
      {\DisplayProof \egroup }

      \begin {bprooftree}
        \AxiomC {$\Sigma $}
        \UnaryInfC {$\Gamma ' \vdash  \psi '$}
        \LeftLabel {\small  (R)}
        \UnaryInfC {$S := \Gamma  \vdash  \psi $}
        \LeftLabel {\small (wk$_x$)}
        \UnaryInfC {$\Gamma , x : \phi  \vdash  \psi $}
      \end {bprooftree}


    we can reduce it to:


    \usepackage {bussproofs, amsopn, amssymb, mathrsfs, amsmath}
    \newenvironment {bprooftree}
      {\leavevmode \hbox \bgroup }
      {\DisplayProof \egroup }

      \begin {bprooftree}
        \AxiomC {$\Sigma $}
        \UnaryInfC {$\Gamma ' \vdash  \psi '$}
        \LeftLabel {\small (wk$_x$)}
        \UnaryInfC {$\Gamma ', x : \phi   \vdash  \psi '$}
        \LeftLabel {\small  (R)}
        \UnaryInfC {$\Gamma , x : \phi   \vdash  \psi $}
      \end {bprooftree}


    if S is neither a companion or a bud. Otherwise:

If S is a bud, we cannot reduce.

If S is a companion for some cycle C, and for C and all nested cycles C' we have that \theta _{C'}(y) = x only if x \Rightarrow  y, for all y \in  \text {fv}(\phi ), then we add x : \phi  to all sequents along the cycle and its internal overlapping cycles. At branches that do not contain the overlapping internal cycles, we add a weakening step for x : \phi .
    This entire process relies on labels being "globally fresh".

Given a cyclic proof


    \usepackage {bussproofs, amsopn, amssymb, mathrsfs, amsmath}
    \newenvironment {bprooftree}
      {\leavevmode \hbox \bgroup }
      {\DisplayProof \egroup }

      \begin {bprooftree}
        \AxiomC {$*\ \ \Gamma ' \vdash  \phi '$}
        \UnaryInfC {$\vdots $}
        \UnaryInfC {$*\ \ \Gamma  \vdash  \phi $}
      \end {bprooftree}


    with cycle C with maps (f , \theta ), we define its unfolding as the proof


    \usepackage {bussproofs, amsopn, amssymb, mathrsfs, amsmath}
    \newenvironment {bprooftree}
      {\leavevmode \hbox \bgroup }
      {\DisplayProof \egroup }

      \begin {bprooftree}
        \AxiomC {$*\ \ (f', \theta ')(\Gamma ' \vdash  \phi ')$}
        \UnaryInfC {$(f', \theta ')(\vdots )$}
        \UnaryInfC {$*\ \ \Gamma ' \vdash  \phi '$}
        \UnaryInfC {$\vdots $}
        \UnaryInfC {$\Gamma  \vdash  \phi $}
      \end {bprooftree}


    where we define:

       \begin {align*}              f'(x) := \begin {cases}         f(x) & \text {if } x \in  \text {lbl}(\text {com}(C))\\         (x)' & \text {otherwise}        \end {cases}\\       \theta '(x) := \begin {cases}         \theta (x) & \text {if } x \in  \text {fv}(\text {com}(C))\\         (x)' & \text {otherwise}        \end {cases}          \end {align*}

In the previous iteration of the proof system, we just took contexts as sets of formulae. This is problematic from a proof reduction point of view. Consider implication reduction (cut-elimination):


    \usepackage {bussproofs, amsopn, amssymb, mathrsfs, amsmath}
    \newenvironment {bprooftree}
      {\leavevmode \hbox \bgroup }
      {\DisplayProof \egroup }

    \begin {bprooftree}
      \AxiomC {$\Sigma $}
      \UnaryInfC {$\Gamma , \phi  \vdash  \psi $}
      \UnaryInfC {$\Gamma  \vdash  \phi  \Rightarrow  \psi $}
      \AxiomC {$\Pi $}
      \UnaryInfC {$\Gamma  \vdash  \phi $}
      \BinaryInfC {$\Gamma  \vdash  \psi $}
    \end {bprooftree}
    $\ \ \rightsquigarrow $
    \begin {bprooftree}
      \AxiomC {$\Sigma [\Pi  / \phi ]$}
      \UnaryInfC {$\Gamma  \vdash  \psi $}
    \end {bprooftree}


  Intuitively \Sigma [\Pi  / \phi ] is defined as "remove \phi  from the context everywhere in the sub-proof \Sigma , and replace axioms for \phi  with \Pi ". However, what happens if there is already \phi  \in  \Gamma ? We don't know whether the "occurence" of \phi  that is derived from an axiom rule in \Sigma  is the one previously in \Gamma  or not - the same issue persists if we take contexts as multi-sets.

In monad container language: (S \triangleleft P, \iota , \sigma , \text {pr}) satisfies the "disjoint substitution condition" if for all shapes s, s_0 : S, positions p : P\ s, functions f : P\ s \to S where f\ p = \iota , and functions g : P\ s \to S where:
\begin {align*} g\ p &:= s_0\\ g\ p' &:= \iota \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \text {if } p' \neq p \end {align*}
then we have: \sigma \ (\sigma \ s\ g)\ (f \circ \text {pr}_1) = \sigma \ (\sigma \ s\ f)\ (g \circ \text {pr}_1)

(S \triangleleft  P, \iota , \sigma , \text {pr}) satisfies absorbtion (TODO: not a good name!) if there exist an s : S, and f : P\ s \to  S such that for any p : P\ s we have:
           \sigma \ s\ f^{p} = \iota      
    using the shorthand:
           f^p := \lambda  p' .        \begin {cases}         \iota  & \text {if } p' = p\\         f\ p' & \text {otherwise}       \end {cases}

The data for these specialised distributive laws now becomes:

       \begin {align*}            &u_1 : \prod _{s : S} (P\ s \to  T) \to  T \\     &u_2 : \prod _{s : S} \prod _{f : P\ s \to  T} Q\ (u_1\ s\ f) \to  S \\        \end {align*}   

  where the following equalities hold:

       \begin {align*}            u\ \iota ^S\ (\lambda  \_ . t) &= (t , \lambda  \_ . \iota ^S)\\     u\ s\ (\lambda  \_. \iota ^T) &= (\iota ^T , \lambda  \_. s)\\     \\      u_1\ (\sigma ^S\ s\ f)\ (g \circ  \text {pr}^S) &= u_1\ s\ (u_1 \circ  \langle  f , g \rangle )\\     u_2\ (\sigma ^S\ s\ f)\ (g \circ  \text {pr}^S)\ q &= \sigma ^S\ (u_2\ s\ (u_1 \circ  \langle  f , g \rangle )\ q)\ (\lambda  p . u_2\ (f\ p)\ (g\ p)\ q)\\       \\     u_1\ s\ (\sigma ^T \circ  \langle  f , g \rangle ) &= \sigma ^T\ (u_1\ s\ f)\ (\lambda  q . u_1\ (u_2\ s\ f\ q)\ (\lambda  p . g\ p\ q))\\     u_2\ s\ (\sigma ^T \circ  \langle  f , g \rangle )\ q &= u_2\ (u_2\ s\ f\ (\text {pr}^T_1\ q))\ (\lambda  p . g\ p\ q)\ (\text {pr}^T_2\ q)        \end {align*}

During my meeting with Reuben, I thought of a different formulation of the unfold rule for \mu -formulae that might give us better control over substitutions:


    \usepackage {bussproofs, amsopn, amssymb, mathrsfs, amsmath}
    \newenvironment {bprooftree}
      {\leavevmode \hbox \bgroup }
      {\DisplayProof \egroup }

    \begin {bprooftree}
      \AxiomC {$\Gamma [\theta ] \vdash  ((\mu ^\alpha  X.\phi )\ \vec {t})[\theta ]$}
      \AxiomC {$\Gamma , \exists \beta  < \alpha . \phi [\mu ^\beta  X.\phi  / X]\ \vec {t} \vdash  \psi $}
      \LeftLabel {\small  (unfold$_{\theta }$)}
      \BinaryInfC {$\Gamma [\theta ] \vdash  \psi [\theta ]$}
    \end {bprooftree}


  Where the free variables occuring in the domain and image of \theta  are disjoint.

We would then keep the previous fold rule and add the reductions:

       \begin {align*}            \text {unfold}_{\theta }\ x = \text {fold}\ t' \text { in } t &\longrightarrow _\mu  t[\theta ][t'/x]\\     \text {fold}\ (\text {unfold}_{\theta }\ x = t \text { in } x) &\longrightarrow _\mu  t        \end {align*}   

  The substitution  x \mapsto  t involved in a \forall -reduction would get "blocked" by an unfold rule instance, and we would instead change \theta  to \theta [\theta ^{-1}(x) \mapsto  t]. Actually we might need to do \theta [\theta ^{-1}(x) \mapsto  \theta (t)], but I'll have to work this out by trying some examples (see below).

We can derive the (\mu  L) rule much more naturally with this formulation of unfold:


    \usepackage {bussproofs, amsopn, amssymb, mathrsfs, amsmath}
    \newenvironment {bprooftree}
      {\leavevmode \hbox \bgroup }
      {\DisplayProof \egroup }

    \begin {bprooftree}
      \AxiomC {}
      \LeftLabel {\small  (ax)}
      \UnaryInfC {$\Gamma [\theta ], ((\mu ^\alpha  X.\phi )\ \vec {t})[\theta ] \vdash  ((\mu ^\alpha  X.\phi )\ \vec {t})[\theta ]$}
      \AxiomC {$\Gamma , \exists \beta  < \alpha . \phi [\mu ^\beta  X.\phi  / X]\ \vec {t} \vdash  \psi $}
      \LeftLabel {\small  (unfold$_{\theta }$)}
      \BinaryInfC {$\Gamma [\theta ], ((\mu ^\alpha  X.\phi )\ \vec {t})[\theta ] \vdash  \psi [\theta ]$}
    \end {bprooftree}

We start with the cyclic proof:


    \usepackage {bussproofs, amsopn, amssymb, mathrsfs, amsmath}
    \newenvironment {bprooftree}
      {\leavevmode \hbox \bgroup }
      {\DisplayProof \egroup }

      \begin {bprooftree}
        \AxiomC {}
        \noLine 
        \UnaryInfC {*\ \ $\beta  < \alpha  , P^\beta (y', z', x') \vdash  \bot $}
        \AxiomC {}
        \noLine 
        \UnaryInfC {*\ \ $\beta  < \alpha  , P^\beta (z', x', y') \vdash  \bot $}
        \BinaryInfC {$\beta  < \alpha  , P^\beta (y', z', x') \vee  P^\beta (z', x', y') \vdash  \bot $}
        \UnaryInfC {$\exists \beta  < \alpha .P^\beta (y', z', x') \vee  P^\beta (z', x', y') \vdash  \bot $}
        \LeftLabel {\small  $(\mu  L)$}
        \RightLabel {$\theta $}
        \UnaryInfC {*\ \ $P^\alpha (x, y, z) \vdash  \bot $}
        \UnaryInfC {$\vdash  P^\alpha (x, y, z) \Rightarrow  \bot $}
        \UnaryInfC {$\vdash  \forall  x .  P^\alpha (x, y, z) \Rightarrow  \bot $}
        \UnaryInfC {$\vdash  P^\alpha (0, y, z) \Rightarrow  \bot $}
      \end {bprooftree}


    which we can \text {fix}-reduce to:


    \usepackage {bussproofs, amsopn, amssymb, mathrsfs, amsmath}
    \newenvironment {bprooftree}
      {\leavevmode \hbox \bgroup }
      {\DisplayProof \egroup }

      \begin {bprooftree}
        \AxiomC {}
        \noLine 
        \UnaryInfC {*$_1$\ \ $\beta  < \alpha ,\gamma  < \beta  , P^\gamma (z'',x'',y'') \vdash  \bot $}
        \AxiomC {}
        \noLine 
        \UnaryInfC {*$_1$\ \ $\beta  < \alpha ,\gamma  < \beta  , P^\gamma (x'',y'',z'') \vdash  \bot $}
        \BinaryInfC {$\beta  < \alpha ,\gamma  < \beta  , P^\gamma (z'',x'',y'') \vee  P^\gamma (x'',y'',z'') \vdash  \bot $}
        \UnaryInfC {$\beta  < \alpha ,\exists \gamma  < \beta .P^\gamma (z'',x'',y'') \vee  P^\gamma (x'',y'',z'') \vdash  \bot $}
        \LeftLabel {\small  $(\mu  L)$}
        \RightLabel {$\theta '$}
        \UnaryInfC {*$_1$\ \ $\beta  < \alpha , P^\beta (y', z', x') \vdash  \bot $}

        \AxiomC {}
        \noLine 
        \UnaryInfC {*$_2$\ \ $\beta  < \alpha ,\gamma  < \beta  , P^\gamma (x'',y'',z'') \vdash  \bot $}
        \AxiomC {}
        \noLine 
        \UnaryInfC {*$_2$\ \ $\beta  < \alpha ,\gamma  < \beta  , P^\gamma (y'',z'',x'') \vdash  \bot $}
        \BinaryInfC {$\beta  < \alpha ,\gamma  < \beta  , P^\gamma (x'',y'',z'') \vee  P^\gamma (y'',z'',x'') \vdash  \bot $}
        \UnaryInfC {$\beta  < \alpha ,\exists \gamma  < \beta .P^\gamma (x'',y'',z'') \vee  P^\gamma (y'',z'',x'') \vdash  \bot $}
        \LeftLabel {\small  $(\mu  L)$}
        \RightLabel {$\theta '$}
        \UnaryInfC {*$_2$\ \ $\beta  < \alpha , P^\beta (z', x', y') \vdash  \bot $}

        \BinaryInfC {$\beta  < \alpha  , P^\beta (y', z', x') \vee  P^\beta (z', x', y') \vdash  \bot $}
        \UnaryInfC {$\exists \beta  < \alpha .P^\beta (y', z', x') \vee  P^\beta (z', x', y') \vdash  \bot $}
        \LeftLabel {\small  $(\mu  L)$}
        \RightLabel {$\theta $}
        \UnaryInfC {$P^\alpha (x, y, z) \vdash  \bot $}
        \UnaryInfC {$\vdash  P^\alpha (x, y, z) \Rightarrow  \bot $}
        \UnaryInfC {$\vdash  \forall  x .  P^\alpha (x, y, z) \Rightarrow  \bot $}
        \UnaryInfC {$\vdash  P^\alpha (0, y, z) \Rightarrow  \bot $}
      \end {bprooftree}


    which we then \forall -reduce to:


    \usepackage {bussproofs, amsopn, amssymb, mathrsfs, amsmath}
