        \end {bprooftree}

  In cases 2 and 4 we imagine that the weakening rule instance can occur anywhere along the cycle (i.e. not necessarily directly above the companion).

  The idea is that in the left-hand cyclic subproof, either the "even" or "odd" assumption can be weakened away, either before or after forming a cycle. We are considering what would happen if we tried to substitute O^\alpha (s\, x) with something. Our intution for how to handle each case is as follows:

The weaking instance is just removed, since the "odd" assumption doesn't interact with the cycle at all.

We need to unfold the cycle once, then the substitution can be performed, removing the weakening step wherever it occurs. We may need to appeal to bud freshness. Side note: does this still work if O^\alpha (s\, x) is used in an axiom, but anything implied from it is weakened away?

We should unfold once, then propagate the weakening to the axioms for O^\alpha (s\, x), then we can substitute.

    Alternate approach: we weaken along the cycle first, but this requires the cycle term variable substitution to be identity for x (\theta  is "good" for E^\alpha (x))

We should unfold once, then propagate the weakening to the axioms for O^\alpha (s\, x), then we can substitute.

    Alternate approach: push weakening along the cycle first, then unfold and we can perform the substitution. This seems to just be the same as the other approach though.1064mee-0006mee-0006.xmlMeeting notes: Reuben 31/01/25202521Chris Purdy
This week we discussed specifics of weakening along overlapping cycles, and trade-offs of our two proposed approaches:

Defining weakening and unfolding as reductions in their own right.

Only do weakening and unfolding as part of a "hereditary" substitution used in \Rightarrow  and \forall  reduction.
Aside from what we discussed last week, there is still an issue with weakening along cycles, specifically nested ones. Consider the following situation:


    \usepackage {bussproofs, amsopn, amssymb, mathrsfs, amsmath}
    \newenvironment {bprooftree}
      {\leavevmode \hbox \bgroup }
      {\DisplayProof \egroup }

    \begin {bprooftree}
      \AxiomC {*\ $\mathcal {H} ; \Gamma ' \vdash  \psi '$}
      \UnaryInfC {$\vdots $}
      \UnaryInfC {*\ $\mathcal {H} ; \Gamma  \vdash  \psi $}
      \LeftLabel {\small  (wk$_y$)}
      \UnaryInfC {$\mathcal {H} ; \Gamma , y : \chi  \vdash  \psi $}
    \end {bprooftree}


  Even if the weakening is "good" with respect to the * cycle, it may be that there is another cycle that overlaps * which the weakening is "bad" with respect to. This would mean that we cannot just look at the companion above a weakening rule to decide whether we can weaken along the entire proof above that companion. I think that part of this problem stems from unfoldings being "big-step" in some sense, so I proposed that we consider "unrollings" of cyclic proofs instead - a "small-step" kind of cycle unfolding.352mhe-0016mhe-0016.xmlCycle unrollingDefinition202521Chris Purdy
Given a cyclic proof with a cycle *, with cycle map f \rightsquigarrow  \theta :  


    \usepackage {bussproofs, amsopn, amssymb, mathrsfs, amsmath}
    \newenvironment {bprooftree}
      {\leavevmode \hbox \bgroup }
      {\DisplayProof \egroup }

    \begin {bprooftree}
      \AxiomC {*\ $\mathcal {H} ; \Gamma '' \vdash  \psi ''$}
      \UnaryInfC {$\vdots $}
      \UnaryInfC {$\mathcal {H} ; \Gamma ' \vdash  \psi '$}
      \AxiomC {$\Sigma $}
      \BinaryInfC {*\ $\mathcal {H} ; \Gamma  \vdash  \psi $}
    \end {bprooftree}


  we define its unrolling as the cyclic proof:


    \usepackage {bussproofs, amsopn, amssymb, mathrsfs, amsmath}
    \newenvironment {bprooftree}
      {\leavevmode \hbox \bgroup }
      {\DisplayProof \egroup }

    \begin {bprooftree}
      \AxiomC {*\ $f(\mathcal {H} ; \Gamma ') \vdash  f(\psi ')$}
      \AxiomC {$f(\Sigma )$}
      \BinaryInfC {$\mathcal {H} ; \Gamma '' \vdash  \psi ''$}
      \UnaryInfC {$\vdots $}
      \UnaryInfC {*\ $\mathcal {H} ; \Gamma ' \vdash  \psi '$}
      \AxiomC {$\Sigma $}
      \BinaryInfC {$\mathcal {H} ; \Gamma  \vdash  \psi $}
    \end {bprooftree}

The idea is that we push the cycle "a single rule up". Notice that the subtree \Sigma  is copied in its entirety. This clearly simplifies when the rule above the companion has a single premise.
In order to propagate a weakening along any cycle, we can interleave unrollings and weakening reductions: 

If a weakening is directly under the companion for a "bad" cycle, we make sure to unroll that "bad" cycle first before unrolling any others!

If a weakening is directly under the companion for any single cycle, then we unroll that cycle one step, and push the weakening up one step.
  The "good"-ness of the cycle with respect to the weakening instance is, in this setup, only used to decide which cycle to unroll first when reaching a companion for multiple cycles.1066mee-0005mee-0005.xmlMeeting notes: Reuben 24/01/252025127Chris Purdy
Reuben made a point that we need to be careful when weakening away labels and reintroducing them that no name clashes occur. We decided to adopt something that seems like a variant of Barendregt's variable convention - essentially, newly introduced labels and formula variables are considered fresh with respect to the entire proof below the rule instance that introduces them.
In trying to define reudctions in the new system with weakening, it turns out that we have a problem. The issue arises when you consdier \Rightarrow -reduction in a particular case. We ideally want the tree:


    \usepackage {bussproofs, amsopn, amssymb, mathrsfs, amsmath}
    \newenvironment {bprooftree}
      {\leavevmode \hbox \bgroup }
      {\DisplayProof \egroup }

    \begin {bprooftree}
      \AxiomC {$\Sigma $}
      \UnaryInfC {$\mathcal {H} ; \Gamma  , x : \phi  \vdash  \psi $}
      \LeftLabel {\small  (wk$_y$)}
      \UnaryInfC {$\mathcal {H} ; \Gamma  , y : \chi , x : \phi  \vdash  \psi $}
      \LeftLabel {\small  (imp-intro$_x$)}
      \UnaryInfC {$\mathcal {H} ; \Gamma , y : \chi  \vdash  \phi  \Rightarrow  \psi $}

      \AxiomC {$\Pi $}
      \UnaryInfC {$\mathcal {H} ; \Gamma , y : \chi  \vdash  \phi $}

      \BinaryInfC {$\mathcal {H} ; \Gamma , y : \chi  \vdash  \psi $}
    \end {bprooftree}


  to reduce to something like:


    \usepackage {bussproofs, amsopn, amssymb, mathrsfs, amsmath}
    \newenvironment {bprooftree}
      {\leavevmode \hbox \bgroup }
      {\DisplayProof \egroup }

    \begin {bprooftree}
      \AxiomC {$\Sigma [\Pi  / x]$}
      \UnaryInfC {$\mathcal {H} ; \Gamma , y : \chi  \vdash  \psi $}
    \end {bprooftree}


  with some sensible notion of substitution. However, notice that the y : \chi  which is required as a hypothesis in the subproof \Pi  is weakened away. This is problematic: wherever in \Sigma  we have \phi  being derived by an axiom rule, we want to replace it with the proof \Pi , but we cannot since y : \chi  will not be in the context at that axiom.
The solution here is to "push the weakening further up \Sigma ", but this is not always possible. Consider this possible fragment of a cyclic proof (the cycle denoted by *):


    \usepackage {bussproofs, amsopn, amssymb, mathrsfs, amsmath}
    \newenvironment {bprooftree}
      {\leavevmode \hbox \bgroup }
      {\DisplayProof \egroup }

    \begin {bprooftree}
      \AxiomC {*\ $\mathcal {H} ; \Gamma ' \vdash  \psi '$}
      \UnaryInfC {$\vdots $}
      \UnaryInfC {*\ $\mathcal {H} ; \Gamma  \vdash  \psi $}
      \LeftLabel {\small  (wk$_y$)}
      \UnaryInfC {$\mathcal {H} ; \Gamma , y : \chi  \vdash  \psi $}
    \end {bprooftree}


  We can only push the weakening past the companion of the cycle if there are no free formulae variables in \chi  that "interact badly" with the induced substitution along the cycle. As in, it could be that for the induced substitution \theta  on formula variables along this cycle, we have \chi  \neq  \theta (\chi ). This would mean that adding y : \chi  to the companion and bud would invalidate the cycle. Call weakingings that don't interact badly with a cycle "good weakenings" for now.
I wonder if nested cycles make this more complicated: if a weakening is good with respect to the "top-most" cycle, can you guarantee that it is good for any "sub-cycles" in the subproof above the companion? I have a feeling that you can guarantee this (Edit: you probably cannot guarantee this).
It also seems that if you start with a cyclic proof where weakenings are only used immediately after buds, then they will always be good with respect to any cycles that might be produced via unfolding. We need to prove that this is the case.
Objectives after this meeting:

Define weakening reduction, taking it to be stuck at a companion if the weakening is not good w.r.t. the cycle(s) corresponding to that companion. Pay extra care to possiblility of nested cycles, and also we should assume CNF as it looks like some of our intutions are based on taking it as given.

Define other reductions on "weakening normal forms", making sure that "good-ness of weakenings" is preserved by these.

Show that a proof where weakening rules are only used below buds doesn't get stuck in any reduction sequence.1068mee-0004mee-0004.xmlMeeting notes: Reuben 17/01/252025120Chris Purdy
Reuben and I discussed the explicit weakening rule, and specifics of how different notions of context interact with reductions of proofs.
We decided that the proof system with an explicit weakening rule, and requirement for "bud freshness" (i.e. free variables in the companion and bud must be disjoint). My goal for the next week is to write up the proof system with these extras in detail, and define all the proof reductions.481not-0010not-0010.xmlContexts and reduction in natural deduction2025120Chris Purdy
In the previous iteration of the proof system, we just took contexts as sets of formulae. This is problematic from a proof reduction point of view. Consider implication reduction (cut-elimination):


    \usepackage {bussproofs, amsopn, amssymb, mathrsfs, amsmath}
    \newenvironment {bprooftree}
      {\leavevmode \hbox \bgroup }
      {\DisplayProof \egroup }

    \begin {bprooftree}
      \AxiomC {$\Sigma $}
      \UnaryInfC {$\Gamma , \phi  \vdash  \psi $}
      \UnaryInfC {$\Gamma  \vdash  \phi  \Rightarrow  \psi $}
      \AxiomC {$\Pi $}
      \UnaryInfC {$\Gamma  \vdash  \phi $}
      \BinaryInfC {$\Gamma  \vdash  \psi $}
    \end {bprooftree}
    $\ \ \rightsquigarrow $
    \begin {bprooftree}
      \AxiomC {$\Sigma [\Pi  / \phi ]$}
      \UnaryInfC {$\Gamma  \vdash  \psi $}
    \end {bprooftree}


  Intuitively \Sigma [\Pi  / \phi ] is defined as "remove \phi  from the context everywhere in the sub-proof \Sigma , and replace axioms for \phi  with \Pi ". However, what happens if there is already \phi  \in  \Gamma ? We don't know whether the "occurence" of \phi  that is derived from an axiom rule in \Sigma  is the one previously in \Gamma  or not - the same issue persists if we take contexts as multi-sets.
Pfenning's notes on natural deduction deal with this by using hypotheses labelled with variables, with the axiom and implication introduction rules specifying the variable name of the hypothesis they discharge/introduce. In traditional natural deduction systems, essentially the same approach is taken, but with a "de Bruijn index" approach instead of variable labels. Taking one of these approaches makes it very clear during \Rightarrow -reduction which hypotheses is being "eliminated" from the context.
We are going to take the approach in Pfenning's notes, and label each occurence of a formula in the context with a variable. The condition for forming cycles will then become something like: "there must be a bijection between context variables in the bud and companion sequents, that induce a substitution \theta  on free variables in formuale such that the domain and image of \theta  are disjoint".1070mee-0003mee-0003.xmlMeeting notes: Reuben 18/12/2420241218Chris PurdyReuben Rowe
Reuben and I discussed methods of allowing \forall -reductions to work in \mu HOL^{ex}.703not-0002not-0002.xmlIdeas for cycle reduction in \mu HOL^{ex}20241217Chris Purdy
We are (still) working out how we can equip cycles with a notion of reduction or "unfolding". We specifically want the property that we can "unfold" a cycle and then replace a free variable along the cycle with some term without breaking the well-formedness of the cycle: lets call this property A.
We've found a criteria that the substitutions along cycles have to satisfy to allow us to "unfold" them in a way that has property A - that is the requirement that each variable is either substituted by itself or a fresh variable w.r.t. the companion sequent. Call this property P.
       P(\theta , B, C) := \forall  x \in  \text {fv}(C) . \theta (x) = x \vee  \theta (x) \notin  \text {fv}(C)   
  If this holds, then we can "unfold" the cycle just once and the resulting proof has property A. If this doesn't hold, the current idea is to translate the proof to a different one where the cycle in question has property P.
The translation revolves around the idea of replacing \mu -formulae with semantically equivalent ones that interact with the free variables of the sequent in subtle way.705#264unstable-264.xmlGuarded \mu -predicates20241218Chris PurdyReuben Rowe
A "guardedness" requirement, where we have that all \mu -formulae have the following form:
           \mu ^\alpha (X : \vec {T} \to  \text {Prop}).\lambda  \vec {x}. \exists  \vec {y} = \vec {x}. \phi \ \vec {y}     
    doesn't seem to work in general to give us the substitution properties that we need to unfold cycles. The issue arises in cyclic proofs such as:


    \usepackage {bussproofs, amsopn, amssymb, mathrsfs, amsmath}
    \newenvironment {bprooftree}
      {\leavevmode \hbox \bgroup }
      {\DisplayProof \egroup }

      \begin {bprooftree}
        \AxiomC {*\quad  $P\ x , P\ y , \Gamma  \vdash  \phi $}
        \UnaryInfC {\vdots }
        \UnaryInfC {*\quad  $P\ y , P\ x , \Gamma ' \vdash  \phi '$}
      \end {bprooftree}


    where x and y don't appear as arguments to any \mu -predicates along the cycle.708#265unstable-265.xmlGuard the whole context?20241218Chris PurdyReuben Rowe
We might be able to "extend the guard" to all variables in a sequent by instead having \mu -formulae of the form:
           \forall  \vec {z} . (\mu ^\alpha (X : \vec {T} \to  \text {Prop}).\lambda  \vec {x}. \exists  \vec {y} = (\vec {x},\vec {z}). \phi \ \vec {y})\ \vec {t}     
    but there is also an issue where this also may not work if \vec {t} is not just a bunch of free-variables...? Reuben isn't a fan of this approach, and I think I agree - it's a bit too "nuts and bolts".711#266unstable-266.xmlRequire the substitution property20241218Chris PurdyReuben Rowe
We could require that substitution property P holds of all cycles for a proof to be valid. However, it's clear that adopting this may lead to reductions getting stuck; it may be the case that perfoming a reduction invalidates the property.
Hence if we adopt this approach, we should also characterise which proofs will not get stuck. This is probably something like those that satisfy the property P when they are r-normal for all reductions r \neq  \text {fix}. For the proofs that don't get stuck, we should be able to prove some sort of normalisation result.714not-0003not-0003.xmlNatural deduction-style unfold rule20241218Chris Purdy
During my meeting with Reuben, I thought of a different formulation of the unfold rule for \mu -formulae that might give us better control over substitutions:


    \usepackage {bussproofs, amsopn, amssymb, mathrsfs, amsmath}
    \newenvironment {bprooftree}
      {\leavevmode \hbox \bgroup }
      {\DisplayProof \egroup }

    \begin {bprooftree}
      \AxiomC {$\Gamma [\theta ] \vdash  ((\mu ^\alpha  X.\phi )\ \vec {t})[\theta ]$}
      \AxiomC {$\Gamma , \exists \beta  < \alpha . \phi [\mu ^\beta  X.\phi  / X]\ \vec {t} \vdash  \psi $}
      \LeftLabel {\small  (unfold$_{\theta }$)}
      \BinaryInfC {$\Gamma [\theta ] \vdash  \psi [\theta ]$}
    \end {bprooftree}


  Where the free variables occuring in the domain and image of \theta  are disjoint.
We would then keep the previous fold rule and add the reductions:

       \begin {align*}            \text {unfold}_{\theta }\ x = \text {fold}\ t' \text { in } t &\longrightarrow _\mu  t[\theta ][t'/x]\\     \text {fold}\ (\text {unfold}_{\theta }\ x = t \text { in } x) &\longrightarrow _\mu  t        \end {align*}   

  The substitution  x \mapsto  t involved in a \forall -reduction would get "blocked" by an unfold rule instance, and we would instead change \theta  to \theta [\theta ^{-1}(x) \mapsto  t]. Actually we might need to do \theta [\theta ^{-1}(x) \mapsto  \theta (t)], but I'll have to work this out by trying some examples (see below).
We can derive the (\mu  L) rule much more naturally with this formulation of unfold:


    \usepackage {bussproofs, amsopn, amssymb, mathrsfs, amsmath}
    \newenvironment {bprooftree}
      {\leavevmode \hbox \bgroup }
      {\DisplayProof \egroup }

    \begin {bprooftree}
      \AxiomC {}
      \LeftLabel {\small  (ax)}
      \UnaryInfC {$\Gamma [\theta ], ((\mu ^\alpha  X.\phi )\ \vec {t})[\theta ] \vdash  ((\mu ^\alpha  X.\phi )\ \vec {t})[\theta ]$}
      \AxiomC {$\Gamma , \exists \beta  < \alpha . \phi [\mu ^\beta  X.\phi  / X]\ \vec {t} \vdash  \psi $}
      \LeftLabel {\small  (unfold$_{\theta }$)}
      \BinaryInfC {$\Gamma [\theta ], ((\mu ^\alpha  X.\phi )\ \vec {t})[\theta ] \vdash  \psi [\theta ]$}
    \end {bprooftree}
