fr:mainmatter.fr:p:
Let (T, \delta ) be a cyclic tree, and let (V, A, \delta , r, s, t) be its graph representation (TODO: define this). The cycle-quotient of (T, \delta ), denoted T/_\delta  is the graph (V/_\delta , A/_\delta , r, s/_\delta , t/_\delta ) where:

       \begin {align*}            V/_\delta  &:= V/_{\sim ^*_\delta }\\     A/_\delta  &:= A\\     s/_\delta (a) &:= [s(a)]_{\sim ^*_\delta }\\     t/_\delta (a) &:= [t(a)]_{\sim ^*_\delta }        \end {align*}   

  where \sim ^*_\delta  is the reflexive-transitive-symmetric closure of \sim _\delta :

       \begin {align*}            x \sim _\delta  y \iff  \delta (x) = y        \end {align*}

Given a rooted (directed multi) graph (V,A,r), we calculate the "spanning cyclic tree" \text {SCT}(V,A,r) using a graph traversal as follows.

       \begin {align*}            \text {SCT}(V,A,r) := \bigcup _{v \in  A(r)} \text {SCT}^\prime  (\epsilon , v, \emptyset , (\{\epsilon \}, \emptyset ))        \end {align*}   

  where

       \begin {align*}            \text {SCT}^\prime  (p , v , C , (T , \delta ))\ &|\ v = r := (T \cup  \{pv\} , \delta  \cup  \{(pv , \epsilon )\})\\     &|\ qv \in  C := (T \cup  \{pv\} , \delta  \cup  \{(pv , qv)\})\\     &|\ A(v) = \emptyset  := (T \cup  \{pv\} , \delta )\\     &|\ \text {otherwise} := \bigcup _{v^\prime  \in  A(v)} \text {SCT}^\prime  (pv, v^\prime , C \cup  \{pv\}, (T \cup  \{pv\}, \delta ))        \end {align*}   

  where v is the current vertex, p is the path from the root r to the current vertex and C \subset  V^* is the set of "previously visited" vertices.

During my meeting with Reuben, I thought of a different formulation of the unfold rule for \mu -formulae that might give us better control over substitutions:


    \usepackage {bussproofs, amsopn, amssymb, mathrsfs, amsmath}
    \newenvironment {bprooftree}
      {\leavevmode \hbox \bgroup }
      {\DisplayProof \egroup }

    \begin {bprooftree}
      \AxiomC {$\Gamma [\theta ] \vdash  ((\mu ^\alpha  X.\phi )\ \vec {t})[\theta ]$}
      \AxiomC {$\Gamma , \exists \beta  < \alpha . \phi [\mu ^\beta  X.\phi  / X]\ \vec {t} \vdash  \psi $}
      \LeftLabel {\small  (unfold$_{\theta }$)}
      \BinaryInfC {$\Gamma [\theta ] \vdash  \psi [\theta ]$}
    \end {bprooftree}


  Where the free variables occuring in the domain and image of \theta  are disjoint.

We would then keep the previous fold rule and add the reductions:

       \begin {align*}            \text {unfold}_{\theta }\ x = \text {fold}\ t' \text { in } t &\longrightarrow _\mu  t[\theta ][t'/x]\\     \text {fold}\ (\text {unfold}_{\theta }\ x = t \text { in } x) &\longrightarrow _\mu  t        \end {align*}   

  The substitution  x \mapsto  t involved in a \forall -reduction would get "blocked" by an unfold rule instance, and we would instead change \theta  to \theta [\theta ^{-1}(x) \mapsto  t]. Actually we might need to do \theta [\theta ^{-1}(x) \mapsto  \theta (t)], but I'll have to work this out by trying some examples (see below).

We can derive the (\mu  L) rule much more naturally with this formulation of unfold:


    \usepackage {bussproofs, amsopn, amssymb, mathrsfs, amsmath}
    \newenvironment {bprooftree}
      {\leavevmode \hbox \bgroup }
      {\DisplayProof \egroup }

    \begin {bprooftree}
      \AxiomC {}
      \LeftLabel {\small  (ax)}
      \UnaryInfC {$\Gamma [\theta ], ((\mu ^\alpha  X.\phi )\ \vec {t})[\theta ] \vdash  ((\mu ^\alpha  X.\phi )\ \vec {t})[\theta ]$}
      \AxiomC {$\Gamma , \exists \beta  < \alpha . \phi [\mu ^\beta  X.\phi  / X]\ \vec {t} \vdash  \psi $}
      \LeftLabel {\small  (unfold$_{\theta }$)}
      \BinaryInfC {$\Gamma [\theta ], ((\mu ^\alpha  X.\phi )\ \vec {t})[\theta ] \vdash  \psi [\theta ]$}
    \end {bprooftree}

We start with the cyclic proof:


    \usepackage {bussproofs, amsopn, amssymb, mathrsfs, amsmath}
    \newenvironment {bprooftree}
      {\leavevmode \hbox \bgroup }
      {\DisplayProof \egroup }

      \begin {bprooftree}
        \AxiomC {}
        \noLine 
        \UnaryInfC {*\ \ $\beta  < \alpha  , P^\beta (y', z', x') \vdash  \bot $}
        \AxiomC {}
        \noLine 
        \UnaryInfC {*\ \ $\beta  < \alpha  , P^\beta (z', x', y') \vdash  \bot $}
        \BinaryInfC {$\beta  < \alpha  , P^\beta (y', z', x') \vee  P^\beta (z', x', y') \vdash  \bot $}
        \UnaryInfC {$\exists \beta  < \alpha .P^\beta (y', z', x') \vee  P^\beta (z', x', y') \vdash  \bot $}
        \LeftLabel {\small  $(\mu  L)$}
        \RightLabel {$\theta $}
        \UnaryInfC {*\ \ $P^\alpha (x, y, z) \vdash  \bot $}
        \UnaryInfC {$\vdash  P^\alpha (x, y, z) \Rightarrow  \bot $}
        \UnaryInfC {$\vdash  \forall  x .  P^\alpha (x, y, z) \Rightarrow  \bot $}
        \UnaryInfC {$\vdash  P^\alpha (0, y, z) \Rightarrow  \bot $}
      \end {bprooftree}


    which we can \text {fix}-reduce to:


    \usepackage {bussproofs, amsopn, amssymb, mathrsfs, amsmath}
    \newenvironment {bprooftree}
      {\leavevmode \hbox \bgroup }
      {\DisplayProof \egroup }

      \begin {bprooftree}
        \AxiomC {}
        \noLine 
        \UnaryInfC {*$_1$\ \ $\beta  < \alpha ,\gamma  < \beta  , P^\gamma (z'',x'',y'') \vdash  \bot $}
        \AxiomC {}
        \noLine 
        \UnaryInfC {*$_1$\ \ $\beta  < \alpha ,\gamma  < \beta  , P^\gamma (x'',y'',z'') \vdash  \bot $}
        \BinaryInfC {$\beta  < \alpha ,\gamma  < \beta  , P^\gamma (z'',x'',y'') \vee  P^\gamma (x'',y'',z'') \vdash  \bot $}
        \UnaryInfC {$\beta  < \alpha ,\exists \gamma  < \beta .P^\gamma (z'',x'',y'') \vee  P^\gamma (x'',y'',z'') \vdash  \bot $}
        \LeftLabel {\small  $(\mu  L)$}
        \RightLabel {$\theta '$}
        \UnaryInfC {*$_1$\ \ $\beta  < \alpha , P^\beta (y', z', x') \vdash  \bot $}

        \AxiomC {}
        \noLine 
        \UnaryInfC {*$_2$\ \ $\beta  < \alpha ,\gamma  < \beta  , P^\gamma (x'',y'',z'') \vdash  \bot $}
        \AxiomC {}
        \noLine 
        \UnaryInfC {*$_2$\ \ $\beta  < \alpha ,\gamma  < \beta  , P^\gamma (y'',z'',x'') \vdash  \bot $}
        \BinaryInfC {$\beta  < \alpha ,\gamma  < \beta  , P^\gamma (x'',y'',z'') \vee  P^\gamma (y'',z'',x'') \vdash  \bot $}
        \UnaryInfC {$\beta  < \alpha ,\exists \gamma  < \beta .P^\gamma (x'',y'',z'') \vee  P^\gamma (y'',z'',x'') \vdash  \bot $}
        \LeftLabel {\small  $(\mu  L)$}
        \RightLabel {$\theta '$}
        \UnaryInfC {*$_2$\ \ $\beta  < \alpha , P^\beta (z', x', y') \vdash  \bot $}

        \BinaryInfC {$\beta  < \alpha  , P^\beta (y', z', x') \vee  P^\beta (z', x', y') \vdash  \bot $}
        \UnaryInfC {$\exists \beta  < \alpha .P^\beta (y', z', x') \vee  P^\beta (z', x', y') \vdash  \bot $}
        \LeftLabel {\small  $(\mu  L)$}
        \RightLabel {$\theta $}
        \UnaryInfC {$P^\alpha (x, y, z) \vdash  \bot $}
        \UnaryInfC {$\vdash  P^\alpha (x, y, z) \Rightarrow  \bot $}
        \UnaryInfC {$\vdash  \forall  x .  P^\alpha (x, y, z) \Rightarrow  \bot $}
        \UnaryInfC {$\vdash  P^\alpha (0, y, z) \Rightarrow  \bot $}
      \end {bprooftree}


    which we then \forall -reduce to:


    \usepackage {bussproofs, amsopn, amssymb, mathrsfs, amsmath}
    \newenvironment {bprooftree}
      {\leavevmode \hbox \bgroup }
      {\DisplayProof \egroup }

      \begin {bprooftree}
        \AxiomC {}
        \noLine 
        \UnaryInfC {*$_1$\ \ $\beta  < \alpha ,\gamma  < \beta  , P^\gamma (z'',x'',y'') \vdash  \bot $}
        \AxiomC {}
        \noLine 
        \UnaryInfC {*$_1$\ \ $\beta  < \alpha ,\gamma  < \beta  , P^\gamma (x'',y'',z'') \vdash  \bot $}
        \BinaryInfC {$\beta  < \alpha ,\gamma  < \beta  , P^\gamma (z'',x'',y'') \vee  P^\gamma (x'',y'',z'') \vdash  \bot $}
        \UnaryInfC {$\beta  < \alpha ,\exists \gamma  < \beta .P^\gamma (z'',x'',y'') \vee  P^\gamma (x'',y'',z'') \vdash  \bot $}
        \LeftLabel {\small  $(\mu  L)$}
        \RightLabel {$\theta '$}
        \UnaryInfC {*$_1$\ \ $\beta  < \alpha , P^\beta (y', z', x') \vdash  \bot $}

        \AxiomC {}
        \noLine 
        \UnaryInfC {*$_2$\ \ $\beta  < \alpha ,\gamma  < \beta  , P^\gamma (x'',y'',z'') \vdash  \bot $}
        \AxiomC {}
        \noLine 
        \UnaryInfC {*$_2$\ \ $\beta  < \alpha ,\gamma  < \beta  , P^\gamma (y'',z'',x'') \vdash  \bot $}
        \BinaryInfC {$\beta  < \alpha ,\gamma  < \beta  , P^\gamma (x'',y'',z'') \vee  P^\gamma (y'',z'',x'') \vdash  \bot $}
        \UnaryInfC {$\beta  < \alpha ,\exists \gamma  < \beta .P^\gamma (x'',y'',z'') \vee  P^\gamma (y'',z'',x'') \vdash  \bot $}
        \LeftLabel {\small  $(\mu  L)$}
        \RightLabel {$\theta '$}
        \UnaryInfC {*$_2$\ \ $\beta  < \alpha , P^\beta (z', x', y') \vdash  \bot $}

        \BinaryInfC {$\beta  < \alpha  , P^\beta (y', z', x') \vee  P^\beta (z', x', y') \vdash  \bot $}
        \UnaryInfC {$\exists \beta  < \alpha .P^\beta (y', z', x') \vee  P^\beta (z', x', y') \vdash  \bot $}
        \LeftLabel {\small  $(\mu  L)$}
        \RightLabel {$\theta [x' \mapsto  0]$}
        \UnaryInfC {$P^\alpha (0, y, z) \vdash  \bot $}
        \UnaryInfC {$\vdash  P^\alpha (0, y, z) \Rightarrow  \bot $}
      \end {bprooftree}


    Notice here that if we wanted to perform a \mu -reduction at the first (\mu  L) rule instance, we would need to unfold the cycles again.

Let (1 \triangleleft  \lambda  \_ . A, \downarrow ^A, o^A, \oplus ^A) and (1 \triangleleft  \lambda  \_ . B, \downarrow ^B, o^B, \oplus ^B) be representable directed containers. By specialising the equations of a directed container distributive law to these, all equations involving u_2 disappear and we are left with:
       \begin {align*}       v_1\ b\ o^A &= o^A\\       v_1\ o^B\ a &= a\\       v_1\ b\ (a \oplus ^A a') &= v_1\ b\ a \oplus ^A v_1\ (v_2\ b\ a)\ a'\\       v_1\ (b \oplus ^B b')\ a &= v_1\ b\ (v_1\ b'\ a)\\       v_2\ b\ o^A &= b\\       v_2\ o^B\ a &= o^B\\       v_2\ b\ (a \oplus ^A a') &= v_2\ (v_2\ b\ a)\ a'\\       v_2\ (b \oplus ^B b')\ a &= v_2\ b\ (v_1\ b' a) \oplus ^B v_2\ b'\ a     \end {align*}   
  which exhibit v_1 and v_2 as a matching pair of monoid maps between the monoids (A , o^A, \oplus ^A) and (B, o^B, \oplus ^B). Hence, directed container distributive laws of this type are in bijection with matching pairs of actions for the relevant monoids.

Let (A \triangleleft  \lambda  \_ . 1, \iota ^A, \sigma ^A, \text {pr}^A) and (B \triangleleft  \lambda  \_ . 1, \iota ^B, \sigma ^B, \text {pr}^B) be monad containers. By specialising the data and equations for a monad container distributive law to these, v_1 and v_2 become trivial (\text {pr}^A and \text {pr}^B are already trivial), and we are left with:

       \begin {align*}            u_1\ \iota ^A\ (\lambda  \_ . b) &= b\\     u_1\ a\ (\lambda  \_ . \iota ^B) &= \iota ^B\\     u_1\ (\sigma ^A\ a\ (\lambda  \_ . a'))\ (\lambda  \_ . b) &= u_1\ a\ (\lambda  \_ . u_1\ a'\ (\lambda  \_ . b))\\     u_1\ a\ (\lambda  \_ . \sigma ^B\ b\ (\lambda  \_ . b')) &= \sigma ^B\ (u_1\ a\ (\lambda  \_ . b))\ (\lambda  \_ . u_1\ (u_2\ a\ (\lambda  \_ . b)\ *)\ (\lambda  \_ . b'))\\      u_2\ \iota ^A\ (\lambda  \_ . b)\ * &= \iota ^A\\     u_2\ a\ (\lambda  \_ . \iota ^B)\ * &= a\\     u_2\ (\sigma ^A\ a\ (\lambda  \_ . a'))\ (\lambda  \_ . b)\ * &= \sigma ^A\ (u_2\ a\ (\lambda  \_ . u_1\ a'\ (\lambda  \_ . b))\ *)\ (\lambda  \_ . u_2\ a'\ (\lambda  \_ . b')\ *)\\     u_2\ a\ (\lambda  \_ . \sigma ^B\ b\ (\lambda  \_ . b'))\ * &= u_2\ (u_2\ a\ (\lambda  \_ . b)\ *)\ (\lambda  \_ . b')\ *        \end {align*}   

  Bear in mind that, since all position sets are 1, we do not lose generality by assuming constant all of the functions in the equations above. By defining:

       \begin {align*}            \alpha \ a\ b := u_1\ a\ (\lambda  \_ . b)\\     \beta \ a\ b := u_2\ a\ (\lambda  \_ . b)\ *\\     a \otimes ^A a' := \sigma ^A\ a\ (\lambda  \_ . a')\\     b \otimes ^B b' := \sigma ^B\ b\ (\lambda  \_ . b')        \end {align*}   

  we can rewrite these equations as:

       \begin {align*}            \alpha \ \iota ^A\ b &= b\\     \alpha \ a\ \iota ^B &= \iota ^B\\     \alpha \ (a \otimes ^A a')\ b &= \alpha \ a\ (\alpha \ a'\ b)\\     \alpha \ a\ (b \otimes ^B b') &= (\alpha \ a\ b) \otimes ^B (\alpha \ (\beta \ a\ b)\ b')\\      \beta \ \iota ^A\ b &= \iota ^A\\     \beta \ a\ \iota ^B &= a\\     \beta \ (a \otimes ^A a')\ b &= (\beta \ a\ (\alpha \ a'\ b)) \otimes ^A (\beta \ a'\ b')\\     \beta \ a\ (b \otimes ^B b') &= \beta \ (\beta \ a\ b)\ b'        \end {align*}   

  These are exactly the equations exhibiting \alpha  and \beta  as a matching pair of monoid actions between (A, \otimes ^A, \iota ^A) and (B , \otimes ^B, \iota ^B). Therefore, monad container distributive laws of this type are in bijection with matching pairs of actions for the relevant monoids.

Let (A \triangleleft  \lambda  \_ . 1, \iota ^A, \otimes ^A, \text {pr}^A) be a writer monad container and (1 \triangleleft  \lambda  \_ . B, \downarrow ^B, o^B, \oplus ^B) be a representable directed containers. By specialising the equations of a monad-comonad container distributive law to these, all equations involving u_1 and v_1 disappear and we are left with:
       \begin {align*}       u_2\ \iota ^A\ (\lambda  \_ . *)\ b &= \iota ^A\\       v_2\ \{\iota ^A\}\ b\ * &= b\\       u_2\ (a \otimes ^A a')\ (\lambda  \_ . *)\ b &= u_2\ a\ b \otimes ^A (u_2\ a'\ (\lambda  \_ . *)\ (v_2\ \{a\}\ b\ *))\\       v_2\ (a \otimes ^A a')\ (\lambda  \_ . *)\ b &= v_2\ a\ (v_2\ a'\ b)\\       u_2\ a\ (\lambda  \_ . *)\ o^B &= a\\       v_2\ \{a\}\ o^B\ * &= o^B\\       u_2\ a\ (\lambda  \_ . *)\ (b \oplus ^B b') &= u_2\ (u_2\ a\ (\lambda  \_ . *)\ b')\ b\\       v_2\ \{a\}\ (b \oplus ^B b')\ * &= (v_2\ \{u_2\ a\ (\lambda  \_ . *)\ b'\}\ b\ *) \oplus ^B (v_2\ \{a\}\ b'\ *)     \end {align*}   
  which (up to ignoring trivial arguments) exhibit u_2 and v_2 as a matching pair of monoid maps between the monoids (A , \iota ^A, \otimes ^A) and (B, o^B, \oplus ^B).

Let (1 \triangleleft \lambda \_ . A, \downarrow ^A, o^A, \oplus ^A) be a representable directed containers and (B \triangleleft \lambda \_ . 1, \iota ^B, \otimes ^B, \text {pr}^B) be a writer monad container. By specialising comonad-monad container distributive laws to these, u_2 and v_2 trivialise and we are left with:
\begin {align*} \alpha \ f\ o^A &= o^A\\ \alpha \ f\ (a \oplus ^A a') &= \alpha \ f\ a \oplus ^A (\alpha \ (\lambda a''. f\ (\alpha \ f\ a \oplus ^A a''))\ a')\\ \alpha \ (\lambda \_ . \iota ^B)\ a &= a\\ \alpha \ (\lambda a' . f\ a' \otimes ^B g\ a')\ a &= \alpha \ f\ (\alpha \ g\ a) \end {align*}
where we take: \alpha \ f\ a := v_1\ \{*\}\ \{f\}\ *\ a
